    category: 'Medical & Dental',
    date: 'March 10, 2026',
    readTime: '5 min read',
    h1: 'How Urgent Care Clinics Can Grow With a Better Digital Presence',
    intro: 'When someone needs urgent care, they make a decision in under 60 seconds — they search, see who is open and nearby, check the wait time, and they go. If your clinic does not show up clearly in that moment, someone else gets the visit.',
    sections: [
      {
        h2: 'Real-time visibility: the urgent care patient\'s key decision factor',
        body: `Unlike a primary care visit, urgent care is driven almost entirely by immediacy. Patients are not researching you days in advance — they are deciding right now, in pain or with a sick kid, which clinic to go to. Winning that moment means having accurate, real-time information visible in Google Search and Maps: current hours, current wait times if available, and clear indications of what conditions you treat.\n\nGoogle Business Profile is mission-critical for urgent care. Any discrepancy in hours, especially during holidays or extended hours, erodes trust immediately. A patient who shows up and finds a locked door because your online hours were wrong is unlikely to give you a second chance.`,
      },
      {
        h2: 'Online check-in and wait time management',
        body: `Online check-in is one of the highest-value tools an urgent care clinic can offer. It lets patients reserve a spot in line before arriving, reducing perceived wait time and walk-in drop-off. Patients who have already checked in online are far less likely to leave for a competitor — they are committed.\n\nDisplaying estimated wait times on your website and Google listing also changes patient behavior. Even a moderately long wait feels more acceptable when it is disclosed upfront. Transparency builds trust and reduces the frustration that leads to negative reviews. Tools like Solv or Experity integrate this directly into your existing workflows.`,
      },
      {
        h2: 'Post-visit follow-up and repeat visit conversion',
        body: `Most urgent care clinics treat the patient encounter as the end of the relationship. The practices growing fastest treat it as the beginning. A post-visit satisfaction survey sent by text within hours of the visit captures feedback while it is fresh — and for satisfied patients, flows directly into a review request.\n\nFor patients with conditions that typically require follow-up — UTIs, sprains, pediatric ear infections — an automated message two to three days later checking on their recovery and suggesting a follow-up visit if needed is both clinically appropriate and revenue-generating. It differentiates your clinic from a transactional visit model and builds genuine loyalty.`,
      },
      {
        h2: 'Employer partnerships and occupational health marketing',
        body: `Occupational health services — drug testing, workers\' comp exams, physicals, and injury treatment — are a significant revenue opportunity for urgent care clinics that most undermarket online. Dedicated landing pages targeting local employer searches, combined with a clear employer inquiry form, open a B2B revenue stream that generates recurring volume.\n\nA simple email or direct mail campaign to HR managers at nearby businesses, backed by a professional landing page that explains your occupational health services, can establish employer contracts that bring in 5 to 20 visits per week with no additional marketing cost after the initial outreach.`,
      },
    ],
    faq: [
      { q: 'How do I get my urgent care clinic to rank above competitors in Google Maps?', a: 'The three biggest factors are: completeness and accuracy of your Google Business Profile, volume and recency of Google reviews, and consistency of your clinic\'s name, address, and phone number across every online directory. Keyword optimization in your GBP description also matters.' },
      { q: 'Is online check-in worth implementing for a small urgent care clinic?', a: 'Yes, even for smaller clinics. Patients increasingly expect it, and clinics that offer it consistently report higher patient satisfaction scores and lower walk-out rates. The setup cost is a one-time investment that pays back quickly in recovered visit volume.' },
      { q: 'How do I handle negative reviews about wait times?', a: 'Respond promptly, acknowledge the frustration without defensiveness, and explain any steps you\'ve taken to address capacity. Then focus on generating more positive reviews to balance the overall rating. Volume of recent reviews matters as much as the rating itself.' },
    ],
